  "properties": {
    "encrypted": "false",
    "long_instructions": "Applying a sepia filter gives an image a warm, antique tone by shifting the color balance toward browns and golds. This effect is commonly used in photo editors to make images appear aged or nostalgic.\r\n\r\n**✅ TO DO #1:** In the <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black; font-weight: bold;\">SepiaImage</code> class, write the <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black; font-weight: bold;\">applySepia()</code> method to apply a sepia filter to each <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black; font-weight: bold;\">Pixel</code> object. The <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black; font-weight: bold;\">applySepia()</code> method should:\r\n\r\nTraverse the 2D array of <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black; font-weight: bold;\">Pixel</code> objects.\r\n\r\nFor each <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black; font-weight: bold;\">Pixel</code> object, get the red, green, and blue color values.\r\n\r\nCalculate new color values using the sepia formulas:\r\n\r\n<code>newRed = 0.393 * red + 0.769 * green + 0.189 * blue</code>\r\n\r\n<code>newGreen = 0.349 * red + 0.686 * green + 0.168 * blue</code>\r\n\r\n<code>newBlue = 0.272 * red + 0.534 * green + 0.131 * blue</code>\r\n\r\nKeep color values in the valid range by using if statements to check and correct values:\r\n```\r\nif (red > 255) {\r\n  red = 255;\r\n}\r\nif (red < 0) {\r\n  red = 0;\r\n}\r\nrepeat for green and blue\r\n```\r\n\r\nSet the red, green, and blue color values of the current <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black; font-weight: bold;\">Pixel</code> object to the new sepia-toned values.\r\n\r\n**✅ TO DO #2:** In the <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black; font-weight: bold;\">TheaterRunner</code> class,\r\n\r\nInstantiate a <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black; font-weight: bold;\">SepiaImage</code> object with an image from the Asset Manager, then draw the image in the scene without any filters. You can also upload and use your own image.\r\n\r\nAdd a <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black; font-weight: bold;\">pause()</code> after drawing the image.\r\n\r\nCall the <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black; font-weight: bold;\">applySepia()</code> method on your image, then draw the image again to apply the filter.\r\n\r\n<div style=\"background-color: #E0D1EC; border: 1px solid #9660bf; border-radius: 5px; font-size: 1.1em; padding: 15px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"> 💡 <strong>TIP:</strong> Check out the documentation for the <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black; font-weight: bold;\">Pixel</code> class in the <strong>Documentation</strong> tab ⬆️ for help with getting and setting color values for a <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black; font-weight: bold;\">Pixel</code> object. </div>\r\n\r\n## 🎯 Goal\r\n\r\n![](https://images.code.org/f70b0bebf1888d42781e8b9c317cb679-ezgif-7dc192ac03e55e.gif)",
    "mini_rubric": "false",
    "submittable": "false",
    "hide_share_and_remix": "false",
